{
  "doc_id": "12413",
  "text": "A key factor in generating a fusion protein is maintaining the functionality of the individual components. A direct head to tail fusion of two proteins together often restrains the correct folding of the individual components, and hence leads to non-functional or malfunctional enzymes [CITATION_1] . The availability of 3-D structures of IFS (modeled, based on [CITATION_2] and CHI (experimentally determined) [CITATION_3] facilitated the design of the fusion protein. Molecular modeling of the IFS/CHI fusion indicated a flexible linkage between the two proteins, and a three-amino-acid linker of glycine and serine residues was added to confer additional flexibility to the linkage without interfering with function.",
